There remain two important logical dis- coveries attributed by Aristotle to Socrates, Induction and Definitionb. The Induction, however, of Socrates is not, like that of Aristotle, a strictly formal process of reasoning from the aggregate of particulars to the universal constituted by them. It rather resembles the Aristotelian Example or Parab1e0, being a material inference from a selected number of similar or analogous cases to another individua] instance under discussion.
